    summary: "A tent-maker and businesswoman who invited a gifted preacher to dinner and quietly corrected his theology — then sent him out to change cities.",
    story: "When Paul arrived in Corinth, he found a couple who shared his trade: tent-making. Priscilla and Aquila had been expelled from Rome under Emperor Claudius's edict against the Jews, and they had landed in Corinth with their tools, their skill, and their faith intact. Paul moved in with them. They worked together at the same benches, probably talked through the whole arc of what God was doing over the smell of leather and thread.\n\nEventually they all moved to Ephesus. And in Ephesus they met Apollos. Here's what the text says about him: eloquent, learned, thorough in the Scriptures, fervent in spirit, accurate in what he taught about Jesus — but he only knew John's baptism. He had gotten as far as the river but hadn't heard what happened after the resurrection. He was preaching with everything he had and missing the center of the story.\n\nPriscilla and Aquila heard him, recognized the gap, and did not embarrass him publicly. They invited him home. And there — around a table, over a meal, in a private conversation — Priscilla explained to one of the early church's most gifted communicators the parts of the story he was missing. He went on to become one of the most effective evangelists of the first century. She is listed first in the account.\n\nPriscilla's name appears before her husband's in four of the six New Testament references to them — unusual enough in the first century to mean something. A church met in their house. Paul called them both 'co-workers in Christ Jesus' who had risked their lives for him. She was a tent-maker who made disciples. She was a businesswoman who hosted a church. She corrected a brilliant preacher over dinner and helped reshape the early church. She did it all without a title.",
