    summary: "Fifty-two years of faithfulness brought low in one moment of rage — a king who grabbed what God had reserved for someone else.",
    story: "Uzziah became king at sixteen and, for most of his reign, got it right. He sought God. He followed the prophet Zechariah's counsel. He defeated the Philistines, beat back the Arabians, fortified Jerusalem's walls, built towers, engineered war machines, trained an army. His fame spread to Egypt. Chronicles says it plainly: 'As long as he sought the Lord, God gave him success.' That's the whole formula, spelled out, and Uzziah lived it for decades.\n\nBut success is its own kind of danger. 'After Uzziah became powerful, his pride led to his downfall.' It's one of the most compressed tragedies in Scripture. He had built enough, won enough, been praised enough that somewhere the borders of his authority stopped feeling like limits and started feeling like insults. He walked into the Temple with a censer to burn incense — a role God had specifically reserved for the consecrated priests, the sons of Aaron.\n\nEighty-one priests confronted him. Eighty-one. That's not a quiet word of correction — that's a wall of men standing between a king and an altar, telling him he had no right to be there. Most men would have backed down. Uzziah, censer in hand, turned on the priests in fury. In that exact moment, leprosy broke out on his forehead. In the temple. Beside the altar. In front of all of them.\n\nHe was rushed out. He hurried out himself — because the Lord had struck him, and he knew it. He lived with leprosy until he died, excluded from the temple he'd tried to commandeer, his governing duties handed to his son. He died quarantined, buried not in the royal tombs but in a field, because the tombs were too sacred for a leper. Fifty-two years of faithfulness couldn't survive one moment of deciding he deserved more than he'd been given.",
