    summary: "Saul's servant who watched a priest show kindness to a fugitive, filed it away, and later used it to massacre an entire city.",
    story: "He was in the wrong place at the wrong time — or exactly the right place, if you were the kind of man Doeg was. He was at the tabernacle in Nob when David arrived, running for his life from Saul, disguised and desperate. He watched Ahimelech the priest give David the consecrated bread from the altar — the only food available. He watched Ahimelech hand over the sword of Goliath, which had been kept there wrapped in cloth. He watched every moment. He said nothing. He left.\n\nWhen Saul gathered his officers and raged about David's escape — 'Will the son of Jesse give all of you fields and vineyards? Is that why none of you told me he was hiding?' — Doeg saw his opening. He stepped forward. 'I saw the son of Jesse come to Ahimelech son of Ahitub at Nob. He gave him provisions and the sword of Goliath the Philistine.' Every word technically accurate. Every word designed to destroy.\n\nSaul summoned Ahimelech and all eighty-five priests from Nob. Ahimelech defended himself with dignity — David was the king's most loyal servant, he had no reason to suspect anything wrong. It didn't matter. Saul ordered his guards to kill the priests. They refused. These were hardened soldiers, men who had drawn swords before, and not one of them would raise a hand against the Lord's anointed servants.\n\nDoeg had no such hesitation. He killed eighty-five men that day, every one of them wearing the priestly linen ephod. Then he went to Nob and killed every man, woman, child, infant, ox, donkey, and sheep in the city. One man escaped: Ahimelech's son Abiathar, who ran to David and told him everything. David heard it and said, 'I am responsible for the deaths of your whole family.' Doeg's ambition had made him the instrument of something no Israelite soldier would do — and he did it without flinching.",
